The following is an implementation in Python for finding the longest common subsequence (LCS) between two input strings using dynamic programming. The algorithm maintains a two dimensional matrix to keep track of all possible subsequences and their corresponding lengths. For each row, we start with the first string as the first column and scan through it one character at a time, incrementing the length of the current subsequence by 1. Whenever a match occurs in the second string, we update that cell in our matrix accordingly. At the end, the maximum length in any row represents the LCS between both inputs.

\begin{code}
def lcs(str1, str2):
    m = len(str1) + 1
    n = len(str2) + 1
    dp = [[0] * (m + 1)] * (n + 1)

    for i in range(1, m+1):
        for j in range(1, n+1):
            if str1[i-1] == str2[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) + 1
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])

    return dp[-1][-1]
\end{code}

